    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1961-02-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1961-02-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="118"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d118">
                <head>118. Memorandum From the Director-Designate of the U.S. Information Agency
                        (<persName corresp="#p_MER1" type="from">Murrow</persName>) to President
                        <persName corresp="#p_KJF2" type="to">Kennedy</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d118fn1">Source: Washington National Records
                        Center, <gloss target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 306, <gloss target="#t_USIA1"
                            >USIA</gloss> Files: FRC 69 A 6135, 1/1, Director’s Staff Meeting
                        Notes/61. No classification marking. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_STC4"
                            >Thomas C. Sorensen</persName> on February 7.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1961-02-07">February 7, 1961</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>We propose to discontinue the use of foreign public opinion polls as such because
                    (1) we do not want to give the impression abroad or at home that U.S. foreign
                    policy is determined on a “popularity” basis, and (2) we question their value in
                    view of the time lag between taking the polls and using them as a basis for
                    action.</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_USIA1">USIA</gloss>’s need is for political intelligence,
                    based primarily on <gloss target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss> reports and field
                    interviews with political, business, labor, educational and other opinion
                    leaders and only secondarily on public opinion sampling. To protect our sources,
                    and assure their continuing usefulness, these Preoccupation Analyses would be
                    classified and not made public.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MER1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Edward R. Murrow</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="2" xml:id="d118fn2">Printed from a copy that bears this typed
                            signature.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>Approved<note n="3" xml:id="d118fn3">Although neither option is checked, the
                            Director’s staff meeting notes of February 13 indicate that the
                            memorandum did go to the White House. (Washington National Records
                            Center, <gloss target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 306, <gloss target="#t_USIA1"
                                >USIA</gloss> Files: FRC 69 A 6135, 1/1, Director’s Staff Meeting
                            Notes/61)</note>
                    </p>
                    <p>Disapproved</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
